<td valign=top > 
<b> Computer Generated or Photographic? </b>
<BR>
<p>

Computer graphics rendering software is capable of generating highly
photorealistic images that are often very difficult to differentiate
from photographic images.  We have, however, developed a method for
differentiating between photographic and computer generated
(photorealistic) images. Specifically, we have shown that a
statistical model based on first- and higher-order wavelet statistics
reveals subtle but significant differences between photographic and
photorealistic images.  This work has begun to have interesting <a
href="../publications/tr04a.html">legal applications</a> in light of
the 2002 United States Supreme Court ruling that effectively legalized
"virtual child pornography".

<BR><BR>

In related work, we have developed techniques to detect traces of <a
href="tampering.html">digital tampering</a>, and to detect the
presence of <a href="steganography.html">hidden messages</a> embedded
within digital images.

<BR><BR>

<a href="cgorphoto.m">Matlab routines</a>

<BR><BR>

<i>(Collaborative work with 
<a href="http://www.cs.albany.edu/~lsw"> Siwei Lyu</a>)</i>

